    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Asians in America</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Christopher Kui (Asian Americans for Equality) on June 20 article holds Asian-Americans, rather than pitting themselves against blacks, often work with African-American and Hispanic groups for social justice and economic gains</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''When to Campaign With Color: An Asian-American Told His Story to Whites and Won. For Black Politicians, It's a Riskier Strategy'' (''How Race Is Lived in America,'' front page, June 20):</p>
        <p>The Asian-American community is generally depicted in two ways, as the ''model minority'' and in competition with African-Americans for economic and political power.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''When to Campaign With Color: An Asian-American Told His Story to Whites and Won. For Black Politicians, It's a Riskier Strategy'' (''How Race Is Lived in America,'' front page, June 20):</p>
        <p>The Asian-American community is generally depicted in two ways, as the ''model minority'' and in competition with African-Americans for economic and political power.</p>
        <p>While some Asian-Americans are faring well in school and in the workplace, the experience for most Asian immigrants is one of low-paying jobs, cramped apartments, nonexistent medical coverage, overcrowded schools, and frustrating language and social barriers.</p>
        <p>Rather than pitting ourselves against other minority groups, we often work with African-American and Hispanic organizations to raise the standard of living and achieve social justice.</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER KUI  Executive Director  Asian Americans for Equality  New York, June 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
